  // const resetPlayer = useCallback(
  //   () => {
  //     setPlayer({
  //       pos: { x: STAGE_WIDTH / 2 - 2, y: 0 },
  //       tetromino: randomTetromino().shape,
  //       collided: false,
  //     });
  //     console.log(player.tetromino);
  //   },
  //   [player, setPlayer],
  // );

Sometimes this callback function does not setPlayer properly, and through console logging I was able to deduce that sometimes that his function doesn't properly work. I thought I could fix the problem by changing the resetPlayer into a async function,

  const resetPlayer = async () => {
    await setPlayer({
      pos: { x: STAGE_WIDTH / 2 - 2, y: 0 },
      tetromino: randomTetromino().shape,
      collided: false,
    });
  };

But really the problem is that the setPlayer hook function, when it sets the shape with a random tetromino can sometimes give out a undefined shape. The async function did not fix this problem, nor did ensuring that the randomTetromino function, if(randtetro !== undef) then return definedRandTetro. I was able to alleviate the problem though by adding an if statement under the callback.

 if (resetPlayer && player.tetromino === undefined) {
    resetPlayer();
  }

This catches the undefined tetromino and calls it to run again. I wasn't to be fix the problem but I was able to catch undefined tetrominos this way.

I had this problem too. I was able to resolve it by removing StrictMode in the index.js file:
 ReactDOM.render(
  <React.StrictMode>
    <App />
  </React.StrictMode>,
  document.getElementById('root')
);
To this:

ReactDOM.render(<App />, document.getElementById('root'));

